emale":"1205–Overleden","1205":"1205","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","Abt 1205":"circa 1205"},"en":{"Abt 1205–":"about 1205–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1235–Female":"1235–Deceased","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1205":"1205","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","Abt 1205":"about 1205","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d’Évaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel, Jean-Francois, Pierre.","French: habitational name, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, for someone from Vaux ‘the valleys’ (see   Vaux  ), the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Devault  ,   Deveau  ,   Deveaux  , and   Devoe  .","History: Michel Devaux/Deveau from France married Marie-Madeleine Martin in Acadia <i>c.</i> 1693."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaux","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of various places in northern France called Vaux, from the Old French plural of <i>val</i> ‘valley’. Compare English   Vause   and French   Devaux  .","History: Richard Vaux (1749–90) emigrated from Sussex, England, to Philadelphia, PA, in early youth. Calvert Vaux, landscape architect, emigrated from London, England, to America in 1850 and designed several major US parks, including Central Park in New York City (with Frederick Olmstead). — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its variant <i>Veaux</i> and altered form   Devoe  ) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Devoe","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Devaux   or   Deveau  .","English (Middlesex): variant of <b>Devo</b>, itself a variant of   Defoe   in any of the possible senses and thus a possible cognate of 1 above and 3 below.","Americanized form of Swiss French <b>Thévoz</b> (see   Defoe   1)."]},{"name":"Deveau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Girard, Marcel, Adhemar, Alphee, Andre, Armand, Blanchard, Celine, Emile, Euclide, Henri, Lucien.","French: cognate of   Devaux   and, in North America, also an altered form of this. Compare   Deveaux  , and also   Devault   1 and   Devoe   1.","History: Michel Devaux/Deveau from France married Marie-Madeleine Martin in Acadia <i>c.</i> 1693."]},{"name":"Devault","meanings":["French: variant of   Devaux   and, in North America, also an altered form of this or of the cognate   Deveau  .","Variant of   Devaul  , a surname of French origin (see   Duval   and   Duvall  ).","Americanized form of German   Dewald  . Compare   Davault  ,   Dayvault  , and   Tevault  ."]}]},{"name":"Blanche","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname for a blonde, from <i>blanche</i>, feminine of Old French <i>blanc</i> ‘white’ (of Germanic origin). It came to be associated with the notion of whiteness as indicating purity, and was introduced into England as a given name by the Normans. A pale complexion combined with light hair was long an ideal of beauty in Europe (compare Modern English <i>fair</i>, which at first meant ‘beautiful’ and then, from the 16th century, ‘light in colouring’)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Blanche d’Évaux was born about 1205. She had at least 1 daughter with Duc Jean II Dontreix de."},"et":{"Abt 1205–":"umbes 1205–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1205":"1205","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","Abt 1205":"umbes 1205"},"fi":{"Abt 1205–":"noin 1205–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","Abt 1205":"noin 1205"},"fr":{"Abt 1205–":"environ 1205–Décédée","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1235–Female":"1235–Décédée","1205–Female":"1205–Décédée","1205":"1205","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","Abt 1205":"environ 1205","life